Finally a chance to reply! <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>We are to live in a continued state of expectancy for the Lord’s coming, as an event always near.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> <br>
I understand about the Christian <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>church's</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> desire for followers to live in a &quot;continued state of expectancy&quot; but I don't get how an <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>event</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> can be &quot;always near.&quot; Either it is near approaching and then it arrives, it's a long way off and eventually arrives - or it is just not approaching at all. In the case of JC, it hasn't happened in over 2000 years and in anyone's book that is not &quot;near.&quot;<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Near:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> 1. To, at or within a short distance or interval in space or time.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>How “near” did James mean? It could only be a hope, for Jesus had distinctly said that no one knew when he would return. The term “near” here means simply to bring near or to approach. No specific prediction was made, so no false prophesy<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
As DBC pointed out, the problem here is biblical contradiction. James said it was near, but since it didn't happen, Christians are forced to reinterpret it to mean James <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>hoped</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> it was near. <br>
<br>
Mark 9.1 quotes Jesus proclaiming &quot;<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Truly I say to you, there are some standing here who will not taste death before they see the kingdom of God come with power.&quot;</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  If that wasn't a false prophesy, I do not know what is. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>The “last times” referred to here are when Christ shall come a second time to judge. This time stretches from Christ’s ascension to His coming to judgement. Again, no specific prophesy made, so no false prophecy.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
This time will continue to &quot;stretch&quot; as long as there are Christians around to stretch it. Saying it hasn't come YET follows the same kind of logic as &quot;you can't prove God <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>doesn't</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> exist.&quot;<br>
<br>
Edited to add: or as MightyK might say, &quot;the mystical purple carp hasn't arrived in my backyard fountain <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>yet.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->&quot;<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>The answer to this lies within this passage. Not in verse 8 as stated above, but rather in verse 9. “The Lord is not slow about His promise, as some count slowness, but is patient toward you, not wishing for any to perish but for all to come to repentance.” In other words, He’s not going to come until everyone gets the chance to repent, and not when we (or the apostles) think He should come.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
The way I read this, it seems that even in biblical times they were already trying to explain away JC's failure to show. JC clearly told his followers he'd be back in <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>their lifetime</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->. He wasn't - so to cover for him simply blame the followers for misinterpreting what he said and being impatient. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :\ --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/ohwell.gif ALT=":\"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> This is the same thing as with the reference in James…we should always be ready. How soon? Well, it's sooner than it was a minute ago! <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> <br>
<br>
Cute. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Soon:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> 1. In the near future; shortly. 2. Without hesitation; promptly. 3. Before the usual or appointed time; early. 4. With willingness; readily. 5. <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Obsolete.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> Immediately.<br>
<br>
Sorry, but I don't see &quot;over 2000 years from now after you're all dust&quot; anywhere on that list.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Quote:<br>
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
Revelation -John believes &quot;the time is at hand,&quot; and that the things that he writes about in Revelation will &quot;shortly come to pass.&quot; 1:1, 3 <br>
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
- John here is urging his readers to be ready at all times for the Last Judgment and the establishment of God’s kingdom. We don’t know when, but we must be prepared.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
See, I think that at the time this stuff was written down, they DID think the time was literally at hand and would shortly come to pass. But after waiting around several hundred years, they were forced to change the meaning to &quot;could happen anytime, so be ready.&quot; What choice did they have -- other than to admit JC was a false prophet and abandon the religion?<br>
<br>
I will give the last word to Fundamentalist Baptist Minister and biblical scholar Clayton Sullivan (from Rescuing Jesus from the Christians, page 22):<br>
<br>
&quot;Evidence suggests Jesus also expected other dramatic events <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>to occur in the near future</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> (emphasis mine). The Jewish temple in Jerusalem was to be destroyed. The sun would be darkened, the moon would no longer give its light, and stars would fall from heaven. National strife, famines, wars and earthquakes woud take place. Jesus also fortold that that a mysterious Son of Man would descend on clouds from heaven with power and glory. This Son of Man would send out angels to the sound of a heavenly trumpet, to gather the &quot;elect&quot; from the four winds and from the ends of the earth to the ends of heaven.  (Mark 13:2; 13:24-27; Matt 24:7)&quot;<br>
<br>
None of this happened in &quot;the near future&quot; from the time Jesus said it. It didn't even happen in the distant future from that time. But you may continue to believe it will happen &quot;soon&quot; because JC said so. That's how religion works.<br>
<br>
DL <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>What need for new nursury rhymes when there are always new children?</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> - Ione Opie<br>
