<br>
End of Times is just what it says, the end of time, of life, of existence in the way we perceive it.  Judgment Day comes after the End of Times, when all mankind is brought together and &quot;evaluated&quot;, for lack of a better term.  End of Times is natural progression of life towards its end, whereas Judgment Day is kind of like the pivot point between the end of this existence and the beginning of a new one.<br>
<br>
Did that make sense, lol?<br>
<br>
Kate <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#b9a1d0><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/breligiousdebate60574.showUserPublicProfile?gid=luvthatdyl>LuvThatDyl</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 146<br> <font color=#3333ff>(4/21/03 3:51 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=183.topic&index=34>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   end times</span><hr size=1> I personally think the Islamic approach to end times makes much more sense than the Christian approach (no offense to any Christians).  A lot of Christians think they have everything figured out, and if that is the case, then why go through the experiences?  We all know that the end times are going to come somehow and someway.  Humans are not going to live on this planet forever.  If there is a God, then it would make sense that he wouldn't want all the answers so cut and dry, because then people would have little reason to live.  It is like predicting a superbowl winner.  You can have a good idea of who is going to win, but you won't know for sure until the game is over.  It seems like both Judaism and Islam have some &quot;gray areas&quot;, and that helps to give people a purpose.  Jews have all sorts of different views on the afterlife and Messianic times, and rabbis think this is healthy because it means that people will take it upon themselves to live properly and work towards Tikkun Olam (reparation of the world) since nobody knows for sure what will happen.  If people sat around expecting the end, or they were so certain over whether there was an afterlife, then they would be focusing on these things instead of what is right in front of them.  I'm not sure how Islam views people of other religions, but Judaism views other religions as different paths to God, as opposed to being outright wrong.  I feel that this Christian version of end times is telling everyone &quot;we are right, and you are wrong&quot; because it is basically saying that anyone who isn't just like them will suffer here on earth while the Christians will be sitting pretty in heaven.  This just seems intolerant to me.  <br>
<br>
Now that I think back on it, one of the things that started to bug me a little about the Left Behind series is how they seemed to address Jews and Muslims.  They had the one Jewish rabbi go on tv and tell his followers that Christ is really the Messiah, and they made the Muslims out to look like terrorists.  Recall the part where the Muslims are running up yelling something about Allah while trying to kill people?  Maybe that is part of why I haven't picked up the third book yet.  I look at the whole thing as being just as fictional as any other novel, but a lot of people are reading these because they believe it.  I think they tend to play into the whole notion of the Jews being &quot;wrong&quot; and the Muslims being primitive and psycho.  Oh yeah, and let's not forget the notion of the Christians being 100% right.  It isn't so much the message in the books that bother me, but the fact that these books are reflecting what way too many truly feel.  I can't speak for Islam(Kate?LOL), but I can tell you that if Jews put out a common belief that only we were to be redeemed because everyone else is wrong, then this society would throw a shit fit.  <br>
<br>
Stacey <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#9fb7df><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/breligiousdebate60574.showUserPublicProfile?gid=filfilksq>filfilksq</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 111<br> <font color=#3333ff>(4/22/03 8:10 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=183.topic&index=35>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Having fits?</span><hr size=1> Well I think people are already having fits about Muslims, lol!<br>
<br>
Anyway, the biggest issue on the salvation front for Muslims is the recognition of the Oneness of God.  We believe that the only thing God will *not* forgive is if people ascribe partners to Him... but despite what some people think, we're not really big on trying to get everyone to agree with us.  One of my favorite Surah's from the Qur'an:<br>
<br>
Say: &quot;O you who disbelieve, I do not worship that which you worship, and neither do you worship that which I worship. And I will not worship that which you have worshipped, and neither will you worship that which I worship. Unto you, your religion, and unto me, mine.&quot; (109:1-6)<br>
<br>
<br>
I also agree with Stacey in what she was saying about the &quot;gray areas&quot;, and that giving you purpose.  One thing Islam really emphasizes is personal accountability.. it is not an excuse for me to say &quot;some Sheikh told me to do such-and-such,&quot; I have to research and be fully prepared to take the consequences for my actions.  There are a lot of gray areas in Islam, and we can look to scholars to help guide us, but we cannot blindly follow them.<br>
<br>
